Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class MutableRBEnumMap<E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​V>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.MutableRBEnumMap<E,​V>
public class MutableRBEnumMap<E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​V>
extends java.lang.Object
A mutable map from an enum to a value.

This is one of the rare mutable data classes in the codebase. Typically, we will build a MutableRBEnumMap and then 'lock' it into an RBEnumMap in the same method, and then return it. We should (almost) never pass around a MutableRBEnumMap.

    • getOptional

      public java.util.Optional<V> getOptional​(E key)
      #get on a regular Map returns null if the value is not there. We don't like nulls in the codebase, plus that behavior is confusing to someone new to Java. Instead, MutableRBEnumMap has: #getOptional (which will return an Optional.empty() if there is no value for the specified key), #getOrThrow, which assumes the value is there (throws otherwise), and returns the value

      Ideally, since we should never be passing a MutableRBEnumMap around, you should use this sparingly and only get values from the 'locked' RBEnumMap that you'll convert the MutableRBEnumMap to.

    • getOrThrow

      public V getOrThrow​(E key)
      #get on a regular Map returns null if the value is not there. We don't like nulls in the codebase, plus that behavior is confusing to someone new to Java. Instead, MutableRBEnumMap has: #getOptional (which will return an Optional.empty() if there is no value for the specified key), #getOrThrow, which assumes the value is there (throws otherwise), and returns the value

      Ideally, since we should never be passing a MutableRBEnumMap around, you should use this sparingly and only get values from the 'locked' RBEnumMap that you'll convert the MutableRBEnumMap to.

    • put

      public V put​(E key, V value)
      There are very few cases where, while constructing a map, you actually want to put a value twice. Use #put if you actually want that. For all other cases, use #putIfAbsent and #putAssumingAbsent. You can also use #put for performance-critical code, where you are OK with the diminished safety of not checking if you are trying to overwrite an existing value.

    • putIfAbsent

      public void putIfAbsent​(E key, V value)
      Adds a key/value mapping ONLY if there's no value for this key yet. Use this instead of #put for extra safety, when applicable.

    • putAssumingAbsent

      Adds a key/value mapping. Throws if there already is a value for this key. Use this instead of #put for extra safety, when applicable - which is pretty much all the time.

    • putAssumingAbsentAllowingNullValue

      public void putAssumingAbsentAllowingNullValue​(E key, V value)

    • putAssumingPresent

      public void putAssumingPresent​(E key, V value)
      Replace a value under a key. Throws if the key is not already there. Use this instead of #put for extra safety, when applicable.

    • putOrModifyExisting

      public void putOrModifyExisting​(E key, V value, java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> whenPresent)
      This helps you avoid the 'if empty then modify object, else add object' type of logic, e.g. if you have a map whose values are e.g. numbers that need to be added to, and where the first time around there's nothing in the map.

    • possiblyInitializeAndThenUpdate

      public void possiblyInitializeAndThenUpdate​(E key, java.util.function.Supplier<V> initialValueIfNoneExists, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> modifierIfValueExists)
      Similar to putOrModifyExisting, except that this is most useful for situations where you always want to initialize with a non-trivial object (e.g. an empty array list), and then perform operations on it. E.g. MutableRBEnumMap<AssetClass, List<?>> We use a Supplier<V> instead of just V, so that we won't always need to initialize e.g. a newArrayList() even for those cases where there's already a value under the key. Unlike eitherInitializeOrUpdate, if we need to initialize the value for this key, we will still call the update operator.

    • possiblyInitializeAndThenUpdateInPlace

      public void possiblyInitializeAndThenUpdateInPlace​(E key, java.util.function.Supplier<V> initialEmptyValueIfNoneExists, java.util.function.Consumer<V> modifierInPlace)
      Similar to the previous, except that the 'modifier' function does not return anything. This is handy in cases where the modification e.g. appends to a list. For example, in a mutable map of string to a mutable collection (e.g. list or another mutable map), you don't really need to call put(key, collection) to insert a new collection; instead, all you need to do is modify the collection. Here is an example where this overload is easier to read than the previous one: 
         mutableLotsMap.possiblyInitializeAndThenUpdateInPlace(
                     taxLot.getInstrumentId(),
                     () -> newArrayList(),
                     list -> list.add(taxLot))
      previously, the last line would have been the following, which is harder to read, even when properly indented: 
                           list -> { list.add(taxLot); return list; })

    • eitherInitializeOrUpdate

      public void eitherInitializeOrUpdate​(E key, java.util.function.Supplier<V> initialValueIfNoneExists, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> modifierIfValueExists)
      Similar to possiblyInitializeAndThenUpdate, except that we EITHER initialize if there is no existing value, OR modify the existing value. If we have to initialize, we will NOT additionally modify the initialized value afterwards.
